Excellent emulator with many updates in the past (I assume some recent) and decent input options.  A few minor complaints:  Input for Xbox One's right stick doesn't work. It seems to think it's constantly pushing at the top and right, a fix would be greatly appreciated, because otherwise my new Xbox One controller works well with it. I can use my Mad Catz controller for any game that requires use of the c-stick, but it'd be nice if someone would consider fixing this. I'd greatly appreciate it and I'm sure it wouldn't take too much effort.  Second, you can't input save or load state buttons. It seems small, but being able to save on the fly with a button or reload a save state with a quick press of the menu/select key would be so useful.  Third, I wish you could save per ROM. By that I mean save input configurations per ROM, so that when you load up said ROM (either because its name fits the requirement or something else), you didn't have to fumble about, realize you have it set for "Goldeneye controls" and go back to change it.  All-in-all, though, this emulator is great. Maybe not the best it could be, but probably the best you can find and worth supporting with $1.

replyContent: Two settings that can help with incompatible games are the video plugin (plugins section.. gles2glide64 is typically the best option) and frameskip (video settings). In extreme cases, switching the R4300 emulator to interpreter (plugins section) can help. Most games can be made playable with the right settings. Email me for info on specific games.

I use an Xperia Play, I have a custom rom on it, and I overclock to the max, and when I tweak the emulator (low quality graphics, speed tweaks), some of the games are playable. Ocarina of Time is *almost* playable... but not quite. There's enough lag to make playing it for any length of time frustrating. Unfortunately, N64 emulation on an android device as it stands is always going to be a compromise. I wouldn't want to play N64 games (or any other emulator for that matter) with the onscreen controls, because you can't stretch the graphics, or the controls get in the way (and small screen isn't much fun). N64oid runs Zelda at full speed on an overclocked Xperia Play on Gingerbread, but there's no touchpad support (there is on ICS for XP... but ICS won't run at full speed either, and ICS is slow all around). I wish the creator of this and the creator of N64oid would collaborate... because the touchpad implementation for Xperia Play is perfect - in fact the best of any emulator I've tried. But the lack of speed kills it for me. Keep up the good work... I'd gladly pay much more than a buck for Zelda at 100% speed on an Xperia Play.

content: For all those having problems with donkey kong 64 change the R4300 emulator to cached interpreter and the video to gles2rice in plug ins to stop from walking through walls and for some decent speed. It would be great if this emulator came with some decent instructions of how to change the plug ins and what they do and what is the best settings for certain games, it took me a while to figure it out and I see a lot of reviews having problems with speed and glitching. The dynamic recompiler was the reason for donkey kong walking through walls so other games where objects walk through backgrounds it's best to change to cached interpreter and have it with gles2rice video as the other video plug ins slowed the game down. For 1080 snowboarding the R4300 emulator on dynamic recompiler (dynarec) and the video plug in on gles2glide64 for perfect graphics and speed, couldn't start that on other emulators. Would be great if there was a way to have another option of saving each option state for each game once we have them configured too.

Stop by the support forum for a sneak peek or to help with testing.

replyContent:
Paper Mario: gles2rice (Plug-ins section), Auto Frameskip disabled (Video settings).
DK64: R4300 "Pure Interpreter" or "Cached Interpreter" (Plugins section), and "Restart" (Play menu).
Pokemon Stadium: "Digital" or "Both" touchscreen layout (Input settings).
Mario Cart: gles2rice, Auto Frameskip enabled.

replyContent: For the graphics problems in Conker's BFD, switch the video plug-in to gles2rice (in the Plug-ins section), and enable Auto Frameskip (in the Video settings).
